It's common for me to use JSON.NET to deserialize json of unknown schema like this:
```
var expando = JsonConvert.DeserializeObject<ExpandoObject>(...)
if (expando is IDictionary<string, object> map)
{
    foreach (var kvp in map)
    {
        var propertyName = kvp.Key;
        switch (kvp.Value)
        {
            case string s: Console.WriteLine($"{propertyName}: {s}"); break;
            case IDictionary<string, object> obj: /* recurse...? */ break;
            case IList<IDictionary<string, object>> list: /* recurse in a loop...? */ break;
        }
    }
}
```

This fails with JSON.NET on webassembly but that's not Blazor's problem. I'm trying to do a similar thing with JsonUtil / SimpleJson and it sort of works but arrays come back null. so the following json:

```
{"array1":[{"key1":"value1"},{"key1":"value2"}]}
```

`JsonUtil.Deserialize(...json from above...)`

deserializes as if like this: `new Dictionary<string, object> { "array1": null }`

thus this unit test fails:

```
[Fact]
        public void SupportsDictionaryArrayDeserialization()
        {
            // Arrange/Act
            var result = JsonUtil.Deserialize<IDictionary<string, object>>("{\"array1\":[{\"key1\":\"value1\"},{\"key1\":\"value2\"}]}");

            // Assert
            var array1 = result["array1"] as IList<IDictionary<string, object>>;
            Assert.Equal("value1", array1[0]["key1"]);
            Assert.Equal("value2", array1[1]["key1"]);
        }
```

I have a PR which I will submit shortly to "fix" this issue, although I don't know if it's correct because it's possible this is desired behavior... If you want to pull it, great, otherwise I can just maintain a separate copy of SimpleJson such that it does support this behavior, since it's pretty well self contained.

